We read the Old Testament and God's people were known as the "Israelites", but when you get to the New Testament, they are suddenly called "the Jews". How did that come to be?

Here's the answer...

The word "jew" is a shortened version of the word <em>yehudi</em>, which denotes a member of the clan of Judah/Yehud. After the Second Temple period, Judah/Yejud became the heart of Israel, thus <em>yehudim</em>Â became a term for all members of the people of Israel.

Tada!

And here is an overall picture of the progression on their name change:

<em>The Hebrews</em>Â (Moses' time) ---&gt;Â <em>the Israelites</em>Â --&gt;Â <em>Samarians/Judeans</em>Â (Ezra's time) --&gt;Â <em>Samaritans/Jews</em>Â (Jesus' time) --&gt;Â <em>Hellenists-Hebrews</em>Â (Paul's time)

